{
  "answer": "**In the *Manusmṛti* (Chapter 7), the text prescribes that a king appoint \"seven or eight ministers\" who possess specific qualities.[^1]**\n\nNo matching or adapted prescription for the king's *eight ministers* appears in the *Viṣṇu Smṛti*. The work discusses royal duties extensively (especially in Chapters 3–5), including officials like village chiefs, superintendents, and \"assistants in all affairs,\" as well as the sevenfold constituents of state (sovereign, *minister* [singular], fortress, treasury, army, territory, ally).[^2][^3] But it lacks any reference—exact, adapted, or numerical—to *eight ministers* (or even seven or eight). Searches across the corpus for relevant phrases (e.g., \"eight ministers,\" \"king['s] eight,\" \"seven or eight ministers\") yielded no results in *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, and chapter readings confirmed the absence.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 7, paragraph p-0952cb](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-0952cb).\n\n[^2]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 3](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/03/translation/).\n\n[^3]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 3, paragraph p-8e7e9a](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/03/translation/#p-8e7e9a).",
